<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="70" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="70">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="70">
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus umbratilis" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbratilis">Haplodrassus umbratilis</taxonomicName>
can be easily differentiated by from all other 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Haplodrassus</taxonomicName>
species found in Crimea by its terminal apophysis, which has a broad process (Bp). From the similar 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus soerenseni" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soerenseni">Haplodrassus soerenseni</taxonomicName>
males differ in the shape of the terminal apophysis and embolus, and females by having longer lateral epigynal pockets.
</paragraph>
